newsitem.title: USA: CBOT soybeans quietly lower on technical setback.
newsitem.headline: CBOT soybeans quietly lower on technical setback.

text.p: CBOT soybean futures opened quietly lower on Friday on a technical setback following the week's sharp gains, pit sources said.

Trade was said to be thin ahead of the weekend as weather uncertainties lingered. Forecasts generally called for dry weather to persist in the central U.S. Midwest through early next week but there were some outlooks for showers to push further south on Saturday.
Dry weather has been the catalyst for this week's 60-cent-per-bushel climb in November soybeans but traders said any hint of moisture could quickly wipe out that weather premium.

The National Oilseed Processors Association weekly crush report was neutral, traders said. NOPA early Friday said the U.S. soy crush during the week ended July 30 totalled 23.577 million bushels, within the range of expectations for 22.7 million to 24.2 million bushels.

In opening trade, Cargill Investor Services bought one million bushels November while Farmers Commodities Corp sold 0.5 million November, pit sources said. Locals and commission houses wer also said to be light sellers.
At 0959 CDT, soybeans were down five to 1/2 cent per bushel with August down 1/2 at $7.67-1/2.
